[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[VersionToken "3969570423bd82d757846bb9c1cab594218ffca28ccb6c3078ae9e1b250bbf83"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/minor_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

You open 1\D and partner responds 1\S. What is your next bid? 

Do not support what may be a 4-card suit with only 3 cards. Instead, jump to 2NT, showing 18-19, balanced. Partner rebids the \Ss. What do you say next? 

Partner shows a minimum hand, but with 6 \Ss. 3NT is very tempting, and might work out fine, but with 9 \Ss it is probably better to play the suit game. So you bid 4\S and everybody passes.

Bidding 4\S was a good choice. It makes easily, yet 3NT might have gone down.}

